      "content": "wait, that logic looks a bit weird. specifically that line `if action == resource.required_role or (action in resource.required_role...` \n\nit seems like you're treating the action as if it's part of the required role string? and what happens if a user has the 'admin' role but the resource requires 'editor'? the tests pass but i'm not sure it's actually robust.\n\ncan u make it more general? like, let's say if a user has 'admin', they should always pass, no matter what the resource requires. and if they aren't an admin, they should only pass if they have the exact required role OR they are the owner.\n\ntry to clean it up so it's not just checking if the action string is inside the role string. here's a revised test suite to make sure it's actually working properly:\n\n```python\ndef test_permissions_refined():\n    # Admin test\n    u_admin = User(\"u_admin\", [\"admin\"])\n    r_any = Resource(\"r_1\", \"u_owner\", \"manager\")\n    assert check_permission(u_admin, r_any, \"delete\") == True\n    \n    # Owner but wrong role (should pass if owner)\n    u_owner = User(\"u_owner\", [\"viewer\"])\n    r_own = Resource(\"r_2\", \"u_owner\", \"editor\")\n    assert check_permission(u_owner, r_own, \"edit\") == True\n\n    # Correct role, not owner\n    u_editor = User(\"u_editor\", [\"editor\"])\n    r_shared = Resource(\"r_3\", \"u_owner\", \"editor\")\n    assert check_permission(u_editor, r_shared, \"edit\") == True\n\n    # Correct role, but action is wrong (e.g. viewer trying to edit)\n    u_viewer = User(\"u_viewer\", [\"viewer\"])\n    r_view = Resource(\"r_4\", \"u_owner\", \"viewer\")\n    assert check_permission(u_viewer, r_view, \"edit\") == False\n\n    # Wrong role, not owner\n    u_wrong = User(\"u_wrong\", [\"viewer\"])\n    r_req = Resource(\"r_5\", \"u_owner\", \"editor\")\n    assert check_permission(u_wrong, r_req, \"edit\") == False\n\n    print(\"Refined tests passed!\")\n\ntest_permissions_refined()\n```",
